1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,744
Many years have passed since the first spacecraft landed on the moon in 1966.

2
00:00:09,744 --> 00:00:19,972
From then until now, there have been many additional attempts with some succeeding and others failing.

3
00:00:19,972 --> 00:00:25,255
Here is a short history of some of these attempts.

4
00:00:25,255 --> 00:00:32,647
The Soviet Union’s Luna 9 spacecraft was the first to land on the moon.

5
00:00:32,647 --> 00:00:38,367
It touched down on the lunar surface in 1966.

6
00:00:38,367 --> 00:00:48,890
The landing came after several other Soviet spacecraft either did not reach the moon or crashed on the surface.

7
00:00:48,890 --> 00:01:00,521
The American space agency NASA says Luna 9 was the first spacecraft to carry out a soft landing on the moon.

8
00:01:00,521 --> 00:01:09,274
It was also the first to send “photographic data” from the moon’s surface to Earth.

9
00:01:09,274 --> 00:01:27,438
Luna 9’s landing proved “the lunar surface could support the weight of a lander and that an object would not sink into a loose layer of dust as some models predicted,” NASA said.

10
00:01:27,438 --> 00:01:35,866
In May 1966, the United States followed with its Surveyor 1 mission.

11
00:01:35,866 --> 00:01:51,319
NASA describes this effort as “the first of a series of seven robotic spacecraft sent to the moon to gather data in preparation for NASA's Apollo missions.”

12
00:01:51,319 --> 00:02:03,141
The successful soft landing of Surveyor 1 “was one of the great successes of NASA's early lunar and interplanetary program.”

13
00:02:03,141 --> 00:02:10,810
Both the U.S. and Soviet Union had other successful robotic landings.

14
00:02:10,810 --> 00:02:17,285
Next, the countries aimed to be the first to land humans on the moon.

15
00:02:17,285 --> 00:02:29,246
In 1969, NASA successfully landed Apollo 11 astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin on the moon.

16
00:02:29,246 --> 00:02:37,861
The U.S. Apollo program sent 12 astronauts to explore the moon over six missions.

17
00:02:37,861 --> 00:02:43,188
Apollo 17 was the last in 1972.

18
00:02:43,188 --> 00:02:49,480
The U.S. is still the only country to land humans on the moon.

19
00:02:49,480 --> 00:03:02,650
NASA officials say the agency’s Artemis program aims to return astronauts to the lunar surface possibly by the end of 2026.

20
00:03:02,650 --> 00:03:11,450
In 2013, China became the third country to successfully land a spacecraft on the moon.

21
00:03:11,450 --> 00:03:18,747
China landed an exploring vehicle, or rover named Yutu that year.

22
00:03:18,747 --> 00:03:30,001
China followed with the Yutu-2 rover in 2019, this time touching down on the moon’s unexplored far side.

23
00:03:30,001 --> 00:03:39,319
In 2020, China successfully returned samples of rock and dirt collected by the rovers.

24
00:03:39,319 --> 00:03:48,615
The mission returned about 1.7 kilograms of lunar material collected from the near side of the moon.

25
00:03:48,615 --> 00:03:58,952
Then in 2024, another mission returned rock and soil samples from the less explored far side of the moon.

26
00:03:58,952 --> 00:04:06,170
China has said it aims to land its astronauts on the moon by 2030.

27
00:04:06,170 --> 00:04:13,838
In 2023, Russia tried its first moon landing in nearly 50 years.

28
00:04:13,838 --> 00:04:21,171
The Luna 25 spacecraft was attempting to land near the lunar south pole.

29
00:04:21,171 --> 00:04:26,942
But it is believed to have crash landed on the moon’s surface.

30
00:04:26,942 --> 00:04:39,708
The country’s last effort before that, Luna 24 in 1976, landed successfully and returned moon rocks to Earth.

31
00:04:39,708 --> 00:04:50,209
After its first lander crashed into the moon in 2019, India made its second attempt in 2023.

32
00:04:50,209 --> 00:04:58,335
The country successfully landed its Chandrayaan-3 spacecraft on the lunar surface.

33
00:04:58,335 --> 00:05:04,745
The mission made India the fourth nation to complete a moon landing.

34
00:05:04,745 --> 00:05:14,631
In January 2024, Japan became the fifth country to successfully land a spacecraft on the moon.

35
00:05:14,631 --> 00:05:19,384
But the SLIM spacecraft landed upside down.

36
00:05:19,384 --> 00:05:29,442
This caused some power and communication problems, but the lander was able to operate for a short time.

37
00:05:29,442 --> 00:05:32,251
I’m Bryan Lynn.